t never before published--this book offers the most nuanced picture yet of Einstein's complex and sometimes stormy relationship with Jewish nationalism. Ze'ev Rosenkranz sheds new light on Einstein's encounters with prominent Zionist leaders, and reveals exactly what Einstein did and didn't like about Zionist beliefs, objectives, and methods. He looks at the personal, cultural, and political factors that led Einstein to support certain goals of Jewish nationalism; his role in the birth of the Hebrew University; his impressions of the emerging Jewish settlements in Palestine; and his reaction to mounting violence in the Arab-Jewish conflict. Rosenkranz explores a host of fascinating questions, such as whether Zionists sought to silence Einstein's criticism of their movement, whether Einstein was the real manipulator, and whether this Zionist icon was indeed a committed believer in Zionism or an iconoclast beholden to no one.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aZionism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aAbraham Flexner.  aAbraham Fraenkel.  aAhad Ha'am.  aAlbert Einstein Archives.  aAlbert Einstein.  aAlfred Dreyfus.  aAliyah.  aAmerican Schools of Oriental Research.  aAnti-Zionism.  aArab–Israeli conflict.  aArthur Ruppin.  aAxis powers.  aBalfour Declaration.  aBerliner Tageblatt.  aBlood libel.  aChaim Weizmann.  aChief Rabbi.  aChurchill White Paper.  aCultural Zionism.  aCulture and Society.  aCyrus Adler.  aDisenchantment.  aDora Diamant.  aEinstein Papers Project.  aEinstein family.  aEliezer Ben-Yehuda.  aEmil Grunzweig.  aErnest Rutherford.  aErnest Solvay.  aFelix Ehrenhaft.  aFirst Intifada.  aFranz Kafka.  aFritz Haber.  aGeorge Mosse.  aGerman model.  aGustav Landauer.  aHabilitation.  aHaredi Judaism.  aHarvard University